Ubiquitin, Circadian rhythm, and Redox signaling

Ubiquitin is a small protein found in almost all cellular tissues in humans.

Its primary function is to regulate protein turnover within cells through a process known as ubiquitination. 

This process marks proteins for degradation by the proteasome, a large protein complex responsible for breaking down unwanted or damaged proteins.

The regulation of this process is dependent on circadian rhythm and light environment.

Dysregulation of ubiquitination marking rates may contribute to protein misfolding diseases such as

- Alzheimer's disease (AD)
- Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS)
- Prion diseases, and
- Glioblastomas (GBM).

Here's how it all works...
Ubiquitin's role in Circadian Clock Genes PER and CRY

Ubiquitin regulates the degradation of PER proteins. 

In the circadian clock mechanism, PER proteins accumulate during the night and then inhibit their own transcription by forming a complex with other clock proteins. 

Ubiquitination marks these PER proteins for degradation by the proteasome.

This controls PER levels within the cell and allows the clock to reset for the next cycle.

If the timing of PER is off for any reason, neurons are off and protein misfolding is off.

"The amount of misfolding affects the ELF-UV light signal the cell can make. Bad folding = more ELF-UV release = more neural tissue destruction." -@DrJackKruse 

You can see how important all of this is now...

Ubiquitin-mediated degradation may also be involved in regulating CRY levels.

How Light Environment Affects Ubiquitin  

Prolonged stress, particularly light stress, can lead to increased rates of ubiquitination.

Dysregulation of ubiquitination can lead to the formation of insoluble protein aggregates, which are a hallmark of AD pathology.

ALSO:

Prolonged stress, especially light stress, depletes docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) from cell membranes,

Disrupting the Bazan effect (lipid signaling pathways), and increases the need for methionine because ubiquitin rates skyrocket.
https://t.co/P0dWPswIrh
Relationship Between Solar Frequencies and Proteins:

ELF-UV light refers to UV radiation with wavelengths in the range of 200 to 400 nanometers, specifically those at the lower end of the UV spectrum.

When cells are exposed to ELF-UV light, it can trigger changes in protein folding, stability, and degradation, leading to alterations in ubiquitin marking rates.

"Proteins are biomolecules that are designed to absorb specific solar radiation frequencies that drive cell signaling.

Once absorbed by the atoms in the cells, the light's frequency and color are altered.

The cells then re-emit this modified light as a signaling mechanism, with the emitted light ranging from ultra-weak low UV to infrared frequencies." - Jack Kruse

More about Ubiquitin: 
Ubiquitination is an ATP-dependent process 

It's a post-protein-translation process where a small protein (ubiquitin) gets added to another protein.

It costs around 5 ATP molecules to form each peptide bond during the addition of a ubiquitin tag to a protein.

Sunlight provides the energy necessary for ATP production AND sets up the circadian clock.

The circadian clock regulates the rhythmic expression and activity of various enzymes involved in the ubiquitination process, including E3 ubiquitin ligases and deubiquitinating enzymes (DUBs)

These enzymes control the ubiquitination status and subsequent degradation of core clock proteins, such as PERIOD, CRYPTOCHROME, and BMAL1

"Ubiquitination in particular has been found to regulate the stability of core clock components but also other clock protein functions."

https://t.co/416QtNYHIU

Misfolded or damaged proteins are often marked with ubiquitin for degradation, preventing their accumulation and potential toxicity within the cell.

Process of Ubiquitination
Enzymatic Steps:

E1 (Ubiquitin-activating enzyme) -> Activates ubiquitin in an ATP-dependent manner.

E2 (Ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme) -> Transfers the activated ubiquitin to the substrate.

E3 (Ubiquitin ligase) -> Facilitates the transfer of ubiquitin from E2 to the substrate protein, ensuring specificity.

Attachment:
Ubiquitin is typically attached to the lysine residue of the substrate protein through an isopeptide bond. 

However, it can also attach to other nucleophilic sites, such as the N-terminus, cysteine, threonine, and serine residues.

Types of Ubiquitination:
- Monoubiquitination: Addition of a single ubiquitin molecule.

- Polyubiquitination: Formation of a chain of ubiquitin molecules on the substrate protein

The truth cannot be taught; rather, it needs to be experienced. The work of John Ott is a prime example of this concept. Nature drip-fed John information drop by drop, slowly giving him the experience needed to gain an understanding of a much bigger picture.

John Ott lives on in my mind as a pioneer in the field of Quantum Biology and Biophysics, a celebrity of his time and mine. Do you ever read a book and wish that the author were still alive today? Not for informational purposes or gain but rather just to have a cup of tea and thank them for the work they did.

What started off as a career in time-lapse photography ended in a deep understanding of the connection between health and light. John Ott was famous for creating time-lapse photography images such as the famous waltzing flowers used by Walt Disney in 1950, but his real achievements went unnoticed in his time.

John stumbled across many phenomena in his work photographing flora. When John was photographing the life cycle of pumpkins, he noticed that all the female flowers died and dropped off his plants while the pumpkins that grew outside flourished. John quickly realized that his plants were using the fluorescent lights in his basement as light, while the plants outside had complete access to the sun. Pumpkin plants need both the male and female flowers to fruit and thus John had to start again the next year.

The next year came and John went to purchase the fluorescent lights needed to grow the plants but the hardware store was sold out. John then used blue lights instead of the regular ones without giving it a second thought. Much to John's surprise, this time round all the male flowers of the pumpkin plants shriveled and died off while the female flowers continued to bloom.

John went on to conclude that the sex of flowers can be altered by changing the wavelength and color of the light the plant is exposed to. He later did work which showed that the sex of pups in dog litters can also be altered by changing the light they're exposed to.

John's work is from the 1900s, and I can't believe that everyone is not studying his work. I touched on a few of his teachings today, but there are far, far more.
